      )}

      <!-- Recurring entries (3–4 periods) -->
      {superFreq.length > 0 && (
        <div class="mb-6">
          <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-2">Recurring Entries — upper decile in 3–4 periods</h3>
          <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2">
            {superFreq.map(r => (
              <span class="text-xs border border-orange-200 bg-orange-50 text-orange-700 rounded px-2 py-0.5">
                {r.company} ({r.appearances}/{superValidPeriods.length})
              </span>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
      )}

      <!-- Interpretation -->
      <div class="space-y-2.5">
        <div class="border-l-2 border-orange-300 pl-4">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-0.5">The super-narrative tier is structurally stable</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">
            {superCore.length > 0
              ? `${superCore.map(r => r.company).join(', ')} occupy the upper decile in ${superCore[0]!.appearances} of ${superValidPeriods.length} periods.`
              : ''} This is not a market-phase rotation:
            the same companies persistently carry the highest narrative premium regardless of which quarter
            is measured. The overall Fragility Spread is therefore not a statistical artefact of random
            outliers — it reflects a stable structural tier.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-2 border-gray-300 pl-4">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-0.5">All permanent fixtures are US companies</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">
            Every company in the permanent cluster ({superCore.map(r => r.company).join(', ')}) is
            incorporated in the US. No German or Japanese company appears in the upper decile across
            multiple periods. This reinforces the geographic fragmentation finding: extreme narrative
            pricing is not just more common in the US — it is concentrated in a small, persistent subset
            of US companies.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-2 border-gray-300 pl-4">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-0.5">Implication for the Spread metric</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">
            Because the Narrative quartile is anchored by the same companies period after period, the
            Spread measures a persistent structural gap — not noise. Any compression of the Spread would
            require either a significant RG decline in the fixture companies (via price correction or
            earnings growth) or their replacement by companies from outside the current cluster.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── 5g. RG Change Decomposition ──────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-1">RG Change Decomposition: Price vs. Earnings</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-1">
        For {decompN} companies in the balanced panel (Q4 2023 → Q4 2025): was the RG change driven
        by market cap movement or by earnings growth? RG = MC / (E × 10), so a falling RG can reflect
        either a price correction (MC down) or earnings improvement (E up) — or both.
      </p>
      <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-6">
        "Earnings-led": RG fell and earnings grew faster than market cap.
        "Speculative expansion": RG rose because market cap outpaced earnings.
      </p>

      <!-- Summary proportion bar -->
      <div class="mb-6">
        <div class="flex rounded overflow-hidden h-6 text-xs font-semibold mb-1" style="max-width: 480px">
          <div class="flex items-center justify-center text-orange-800 bg-orange-200"
            style={`width: ${specPct}%`}>
            {specPct}%
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center justify-center text-green-800 bg-green-200"
            style={`width: ${elPct}%`}>
            {elPct}%
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-center justify-center text-gray-500 bg-gray-100"
            style={`width: ${100 - specPct - elPct}%`}>
            {100 - specPct - elPct}%
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-4 text-xs text-gray-500" style="max-width: 480px">
          <span><span class="inline-block w-2.5 h-2.5 rounded-sm bg-orange-200 mr-1"></span>Speculative ({decompSpeculative.length})</span>
          <span><span class="inline-block w-2.5 h-2.5 rounded-sm bg-green-200 mr-1"></span>Earnings-led ({decompEarningsLed.length})</span>
          <span><span class="inline-block w-2.5 h-2.5 rounded-sm bg-gray-100 mr-1"></span>Other ({decompOther.length})</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
        <!-- Speculative expansion -->
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-orange-700 mb-2">
            Speculative Expansion — MC outpaced earnings ({decompSpeculative.length} companies)
          </h3>
          <div class="border border-orange-200 rounded-md overflow-hidden text-xs">
            <table class="w-full">
              <thead>
                <tr class="bg-orange-50 border-b border-orange-200">
                  <th class="text-left px-2 py-1.5 font-semibold text-gray-600">Company</th>
                  <th class="text-center px-2 py-1.5 font-semibold text-gray-500">RG Δ</th>
                  <th class="text-center px-2 py-1.5 font-semibold text-gray-500">MC</th>
                  <th class="text-center px-2 py-1.5 font-semibold text-gray-500">Earnings</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                {decompSpeculative.slice(0, 8).map((r, i) => (
                  <tr class={i % 2 === 0 ? 'bg-white' : 'bg-orange-50/30'}>
                    <td class="px-2 py-1 font-medium text-gray-700">{r.company}<span class="text-gray-400 font-normal ml-1">{r.country}</span></td>
                    <td class="px-2 py-1 text-center text-orange-700 font-semibold font-mono">+{fmt(r.rgDelta)}</td>
                    <td class="px-2 py-1 text-center text-gray-600 font-mono">{r.mcRet > 0 ? '+' : ''}{Math.round(r.mcRet)}%</td>
                    <td class="px-2 py-1 text-center font-mono"
                      class:list={[r.eGrw < 0 ? 'text-red-500' : 'text-gray-500']}>
                      {r.eGrw > 0 ? '+' : ''}{Math.round(r.eGrw)}%
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                ))}
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Earnings-led convergence -->
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-700 mb-2">
            Earnings-Led Convergence — earnings outpaced MC ({decompEarningsLed.length} companies)
          </h3>
          <div class="border border-green-200 rounded-md overflow-hidden text-xs">
            <table class="w-full">
              <thead>
                <tr class="bg-green-50 border-b border-green-200">
                  <th class="text-left px-2 py-1.5 font-semibold text-gray-600">Company</th>
                  <th class="text-center px-2 py-1.5 font-semibold text-gray-500">RG Δ</th>
                  <th class="text-center px-2 py-1.5 font-semibold text-gray-500">MC</th>
                  <th class="text-center px-2 py-1.5 font-semibold text-gray-500">Earnings</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                {decompEarningsLed.map((r, i) => (
                  <tr class={i % 2 === 0 ? 'bg-white' : 'bg-green-50/30'}>
                    <td class="px-2 py-1 font-medium text-gray-700">{r.company}<span class="text-gray-400 font-normal ml-1">{r.country}</span></td>
                    <td class="px-2 py-1 text-center text-green-700 font-semibold font-mono">{fmt(r.rgDelta)}</td>
                    <td class="px-2 py-1 text-center text-gray-600 font-mono">{r.mcRet > 0 ? '+' : ''}{Math.round(r.mcRet)}%</td>
                    <td class="px-2 py-1 text-center text-green-600 font-mono">+{Math.round(r.eGrw)}%</td>
                  </tr>
                ))}
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Key insight callout -->
      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-md px-5 py-4 mb-5">
        <p class="text-xs font-semibold text-amber-800 uppercase tracking-wide mb-2">What drives convergence — and what doesn't</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-700">
          Where RG fell, it was driven by earnings growth, not price correction. No company in the
          earnings-led group saw a significant market-cap decline as the primary driver. This means the
          market has not repriced narrative-premium stocks downward — it simply got left behind by
          accelerating fundamentals in a minority of cases. The majority ({specPct}%) saw market caps
          outrun earnings further.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Interpretation -->
      <div class="space-y-2.5">
        <div class="border-l-2 border-orange-300 pl-4">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-0.5">Dominant dynamic: speculative expansion ({specPct}%)</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">
            In {decompSpeculative.length} of {decompN} companies, market caps grew faster than smoothed earnings,
            pushing RG higher. Tesla is the extreme case: earnings fell {Math.abs(Math.round(decompSpeculative.find(r => r.company === 'Tesla')?.eGrw ?? 0))}%
            while market cap rose {Math.round(decompSpeculative.find(r => r.company === 'Tesla')?.mcRet ?? 0)}%, producing an RG of {fmt(decompSpeculative.find(r => r.company === 'Tesla')?.rg25)}.
            Broadcom added {fmt(decompSpeculative.find(r => r.company === 'Broadcom')?.rgDelta)} RG points
            despite genuine earnings growth of {Math.round(decompSpeculative.find(r => r.company === 'Broadcom')?.eGrw ?? 0)}% — because market cap rose {Math.round(decompSpeculative.find(r => r.company === 'Broadcom')?.mcRet ?? 0)}%.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-2 border-green-300 pl-4">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-0.5">Earnings-led convergence: real but limited ({elPct}%)</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">
            The {decompEarningsLed.length} companies where RG fell show genuine fundamental improvement —
            Eli Lilly's smoothed earnings grew {Math.round(decompEarningsLed.find(r => r.company === 'Eli Lilly')?.eGrw ?? 0)}%,
            Amazon's {Math.round(decompEarningsLed.find(r => r.company === 'Amazon')?.eGrw ?? 0)}%,
            AMD's {Math.round(decompEarningsLed.find(r => r.company === 'AMD')?.eGrw ?? 0)}%.
            This is positive from a fundamental standpoint, but it has not brought any of these companies
            close to RG = 1. The narrative premium persists; it is merely less extreme than in 2023.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-2 border-gray-300 pl-4">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-0.5">No evidence of mean-reversion via price correction</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">
            Not a single high-RG company in the panel saw RG fall primarily because its market cap
            declined. The market has not priced out any narrative premium through a correction in the
            2023–2025 window. If mean-reversion occurs, it will require either continued earnings
            growth (the earnings-led path) or a repricing event not yet visible in the data.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── 5h. Macro-Micro Bridge ──────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-1">Macro vs. Micro: Index Level vs. Company Level</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-1">
        The CAPE-based macro RG (market-cap weighted, index level) and the bottom-up company median
        (equal-weighted) tell different stories about the same market. Both are useful — but the gap
        between them reveals where fragility is concentrated.
      </p>
      <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-6">
        Macro RG source: Shiller CAPE data (S&P 500) and trailing P/E (DAX 40). Bottom-up: company-level
        medians from this dataset, Q4 2025 snapshot.
      </p>

      <!-- Comparison table -->
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-6">
        {([
          {
            label: 'S&P 500',
            macro: macroSP.rg10,
            buMed: buUSMed,
            buMean: buUSMean,
            macroLabel: 'CAPE / 10',
            flag: '🇺🇸',
          },
          {
            label: 'DAX 40',
            macro: macroDAX.rg10,
            buMed: buDEMed,
            buMean: null,
            macroLabel: 'P/E trailing / 10',
            flag: '🇩🇪',
          },
        ] as const).map(row => {
          const gap = row.macro - row.buMed;
          return (
            <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md px-4 py-3">
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wide mb-2">{row.label}</p>
              <div class="flex justify-between items-baseline mb-1">
                <span class="text-xs text-gray-500">Macro RG ({row.macroLabel})</span>
                <span class="font-mono font-semibold text-gray-800">{fmt(row.macro)}</span>
              </div>
              <div class="flex justify-between items-baseline mb-1">
                <span class="text-xs text-gray-500">Bottom-up median</span>
                <span class="font-mono text-gray-600">{fmt(row.buMed)}</span>
              </div>
              {row.buMean != null && (
                <div class="flex justify-between items-baseline mb-1">
                  <span class="text-xs text-gray-500">Bottom-up mean</span>
                  <span class="font-mono text-gray-500">{fmt(row.buMean)}</span>
                </div>
              )}
              <div class="border-t border-gray-100 pt-2 mt-2 flex justify-between items-baseline">
                <span class="text-xs text-gray-400">Macro − median gap</span>
                <span class={`font-mono font-semibold text-sm ${gap > 1 ? 'text-orange-600' : 'text-gray-600'}`}>
                  +{fmt(gap)}
                </span>
              </div>
            </div>
          );
        })}
        <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md px-4 py-3">
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wide mb-2">S&P 500 Historical Context</p>
          <div class="flex justify-between items-baseline mb-1">
            <span class="text-xs text-gray-500">Long-run avg (since 1881)</span>
            <span class="font-mono text-gray-600">{fmt(spLRAvg)}</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between items-baseline mb-1">
            <span class="text-xs text-gray-500">All-time high (Dec 1999)</span>
            <span class="font-mono text-gray-600">{fmt(spLRMax)}</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between items-baseline mb-1">
            <span class="text-xs text-gray-500">Current vs LR avg</span>
            <span class="font-mono font-semibold text-orange-600">{(macroSP.rg10 / spLRAvg).toFixed(2)}×</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between items-baseline">
            <span class="text-xs text-gray-500">Current vs 1999 peak</span>
            <span class="font-mono text-gray-600">{(macroSP.rg10 / spLRMax * 100).toFixed(0)}%</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SVG: SP500 macro RG time series 2000–present -->
      <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-700 mb-2">S&P 500 Macro RG10 — Annual (2000–present)</h3>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
        <svg viewBox={`0 0 ${MAC_W} ${MAC_H}`} class="w-full max-w-2xl" aria-hidden="true">
          <!-- Fill area -->
          <polygon points={macFillPts} fill="rgba(249,115,22,0.08)" />
          <!-- Gridlines + Y labels -->
          {macYTicks.map(v => (
            <g>
              <line x1={MAC_PL} y1={macY(v)} x2={MAC_W - MAC_PR} y2={macY(v)}
                stroke={v === 0 ? '#d1d5db' : '#f3f4f6'} stroke-width="1" />
              <text x={MAC_PL - 4} y={macY(v) + 4} text-anchor="end"
                font-size="9.5" fill="#9ca3af">{v}</text>
            </g>
          ))}
          <!-- Long-run average line -->
          <line x1={MAC_PL} y1={macY(spLRAvg)} x2={MAC_W - MAC_PR} y2={macY(spLRAvg)}
            stroke="#6b7280" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3" />
          <text x={MAC_W - MAC_PR + 2} y={macY(spLRAvg) + 3}
            font-size="8" fill="#6b7280">avg</text>
          <!-- All-time peak reference -->
          <line x1={MAC_PL} y1={macY(spLRMax)} x2={MAC_W - MAC_PR} y2={macY(spLRMax)}
            stroke="rgb(239,68,68)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3,4" opacity="0.5" />
          <text x={MAC_W - MAC_PR + 2} y={macY(spLRMax) + 3}
            font-size="8" fill="rgb(239,68,68)" opacity="0.7">1999</text>
          <!-- RG = 1 line -->
          <line x1={MAC_PL} y1={macY(1)} x2={MAC_W - MAC_PR} y2={macY(1)}
            stroke="#d1d5db" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3,4" />
          <!-- Main polyline -->
          <polyline points={macPolyPts} fill="none" stroke="rgb(249,115,22)" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linejoin="round" />
          <!-- X-axis year labels -->
          {macXLabels.map(({ i, yr }) => (
            <text x={macX(i)} y={MAC_PT + MAC_IH + 14}
              text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#9ca3af">{yr}</text>
          ))}
          <!-- Current value dot -->
          <circle cx={macX(macN - 1)} cy={macY(annualSP[macN-1]!.rg10)} r="3.5" fill="rgb(249,115,22)" />
          <text x={macX(macN - 1) - 4} y={macY(annualSP[macN-1]!.rg10) - 6}
